defaultUnlawful detention claims: family separation default&#xa0;default&#xa0;
defaultJudicial reviews to challenge removal from the UKdefault&#xa0;default&#xa0;
defaultCase studydefault&#xa0;
defaultFaith was detained with her partner for 206 days after serving a prison sentence. Her four children were aged between one and eleven when she went to prison; the eldest child was a British Citizen. The children were extremely distressed, and some of them d
defaulteveloped behavioural and health problems.  
default&#xa0;
defaultThree months into her detention, the Home Office wrote to Faith and her partner informing them that they intended to remove the parents and children together. The family had been separated for two years and five
default months. The Home Office noted the need for the children to “re-establish their relationship with their parents before remova
defaultl,”
default and envisaged that this might happen at Heathrow Airport. It is extremely concerning to see that the Home Office thought it wou
defaultld be appropriate to reunite these extremely distressed children with their parents during the course of their forced removal. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThis removal attempt was cancelled, and the Home Office arranged a new date for the family to be removed using the same method,
default but this was prevented by a judicial review application. The parents were subsequently released from detention and granted leave to remain in the UK. 
